<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>VALEANT COMMITTEE TO INVESTIGATE PHARMACY TIES</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Valeant Pharmaceuticals International said that its relationship with the specialty pharmacy Philidor was legal, but that the board would still form a special committee to <b>run an inquiry into the issue</b>, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/27/business/valeant-forms-committee-to-investigate-ties-with-pharmacy.html?ref=business&#038;_r=0">Andrew Pollack reports in The New York Times.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">J. Michael Pearson, Valeantâs chief executive, said the committee would <b>look at reports</b> by <a href="//www.wsj.com/articles/valeant-forms-board-committee-to-review-philidor-arrangement-1445856795?cb=logged0.2197381549892019">The Wall Street Journal</a> that before Valeant had acquired the option to buy Philidor, its employees had been working at Philidor and using fake names in emails. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Valeant executives have also asked the Securities and Exchange Commission to <b>investigate Citron</b>, accusing the stock research firm of making false statements to drive down Valeant stock. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In spite of its effort to defend itself, Valeant shares fell more than 5 percent on Monday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Valeant also revealed in a regulatory filing that its Bausch &#038; Lomb eye care business  received a <b>subpoena in September</b> regarding payments and agreements with medical professionals for surgical products. The subpoena was part of a criminal investigation. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Valeant had paid about $100 million initially for an option to acquire Philidor.<br />
Philidor had <b>failed to get a license</b> to dispense drugs in California because the state said the pharmacy had not been truthful in stating its owners. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Lawsuits and other information suggest that Philidor then acquired <b>stakes in California pharmacies</b>. One of those pharmacies, R&#038;O, claimed in a lawsuit that it sold a stake in itself to an entity that tried to hide that it was a front for Philidor. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Its efforts to explain its ties, without explaining why it obscured the dealings, only <b>confirmed fears about Valeant</b>, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/27/business/dealbook/in-trying-to-explain-itself-valeant-muddies-the-water.html?ref=dealbook">Robert Cyran writes in Breakingviews.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The best that can be said of Valeantâs unsuccessful attempt to clear the air is that it might help the company see how much more explaining it has to do, Mr. Cyran writes. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.bloombergview.com/articles/2015-10-26/valeant-s-pharmacy-relationships-were-complicated">Matt Levine at Bloomberg View</a> notes that the complexity of the trails among all the different organizations involved indicates that Valeant avoided legal ownership because that would imply responsibility. The company has reassured investors about due diligence and oversight, while denying any control or <b>responsibility for Philidorâs actions</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That <b>strategy has backfired</b>. âIt just seems to have gotten the ownership bundle wrong: Its control wasnât strong enough to avoid problems at the network, but its economic interests are enough to make those problems Valeantâs own,â Mr. Levine argues.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>FORMER GOLDMAN BANKER TO PLEAD GUILTY IN DOCUMENT LEAK</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> A former Goldman Sachs banker, suspected of taking confidential documents, and his source at the Federal Reserve Bank of New York have agreed to plead guilty,<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/27/business/dealbook/criminal-charges-and-50-million-fine-expected-in-goldman-new-york-fed-case.html?ref=dealbook">Ben Protess and Peter Eavis report in DealBook.</a> They will accept a plea deal that could send them to <b>prison for up to a year</b> and may face lifetime bans from the banking industry. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Under a tentative deal with New York Stateâs financial regulator, Goldman would also pay a <b>fine of $50 million</b> and face restrictions on how it handled regulatory information. The settlement would force Goldman to take the rare step of acknowledging that it had failed to adequately supervise the banker. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It would also highlight an embarrassing episode that illustrated the <b>revolving door</b> between Goldman and the government. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Goldman banker, Rohit Bansal,  had spent seven years as a regulator at the New York Fed and his <b>source was a former colleague</b> there. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It is rare for a Wall Street banker to face <b>criminal charges</b>: Prosecutors have charged bankers and traders in just a handful of situations.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>LAW SCHOOLS LOWER ADMISSIONS STANDARDS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Law schools are lowering their entry requirements to <b>keep their classrooms full</b>,<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/27/business/dealbook/study-cites-lower-standards-in-law-school-admissions.html?ref=dealbook">Elizabeth Olson writes in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">About a third of the 204 accredited law schools had entering classes last year with at least a quarter of the class consisting of <b> âat riskâ students</b>, or those with law school admissions test scores of below 150, according to a study by Law School Transparency, a nonprofit advocacy organization.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Admissions scores at law schools closely mirror the results of the state bar exams, which graduates must pass to qualify as licensed lawyers, and they are regarded as an <b>indicator of later success</b> â or failure. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Law schools say test scores are just one indicator and they need the flexibility to <b>assure a diverse population</b> of lawyers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But they are also facing pressure from the <b>lowest enrollment in decades</b>.<br />
Enrollment peaked in 2010 with the economy in trouble, but law jobs started to disappear as the industry adjusted to the economy. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Bar passage rates</b> are also slumping, with overall results slipping to their lowest point since 1988. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Kyle McEntee, executive director of Law School Transparency, said that at-risk law students âhave little chance of gainful employment in order to <b>pay off the debt </b>they are accumulating.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> <b>Alibaba</b> will discuss its quarterly earnings at 7:30 a.m. <b>Ford Motor Company</b> releases its third-quarter earnings at 7 a.m. and follows with a conference call at 9 a.m. <b>Apple</b> and <b>Twitter</b> will hold conference calls to discuss their latest quarterly results at 5 p.m. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>A BANKER GIVING BACK</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The Swiss banker Josef Ackermann played a role in nearly destroying the Cyprus banking system in 2013 and now he has <b>returned to fix one of the banks</b> he helped undermine, </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/10/27/business/dealbook/josef-ackermann-sees-his-role-in-cyprus-as-a-chance-to-give-back.html?ref=dealbook">Jack Ewing reports in DealBook.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Ackermann, the former chief of Deutsche Bank, is now chairman of the <b>Bank of Cyprus</b>.<br />
âIf I could give something back to the people or society, I would like to do that,â Mr. Ackermann said. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI want to demonstrate that <b>we cannot only make money for ourselves</b>, but also that banking is actually something which is a main contributor to the prosperity of society at large,â Mr. Ackermann said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If Mr. Ackermann succeeded in reviving the bank, he would also help revive the country. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Thousands of people lost money</b> after their deposits were seized in 2013 to cover losses that the Cyprus banks absorbed on their holdings of Greek bonds. Many are still angry. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The losses were partly Mr. Ackermannâs work. As chairman of the International Institute of Finance â an industry group that represents the interests of banks like Deutsche, Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley â he played a primary role in <b>negotiating an agreement</b> that provided crucial debt relief for Greece. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The deal caused enormous <b>collateral damage</b> in Cyprus. Cyprus Popular Bank, the islandâs second-largest lender, collapsed and was absorbed by Bank of Cyprus.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The banking crisis was followed by a recession and a real estate bubble. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Bank of Cyprus has since <b>reduced its dependence</b> on emergency loans from the European Central Bank, cut costs and decreased its dependence on borrowed money. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The turnaround is still uncertain. Mr. Ackermann would not get a payoff anyway.<br />
He is paid 68,000 euros, or $75,000, a year and has no other options to profit from the bankâs recovery. </p>
</div>
